The paper discusses the design and analysis of physically unclonable functions (PUFs) with a focus on stability, which is a major concern in the field of computer security. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). The paper also uses information theoretic tools to evaluate the security level of PUFs, which suggests a possible fit with cs.IT (Information Theory). Additionally, the paper proposes a new framework for evaluating PUF security, which could be relevant to cs.SE (Software Engineering) and cs.CE (Computer Engineering). Finally, the paper discusses the implementation of PUFs using Directed Self Assembly (DSA) and keyed-hash message authentication code (HMAC), which could be relevant to cs.ET (Emerging Technologies).
